This page is a supplementary teaching scaffold for static abstraction and conversion.

## Generics

The declaring module owns a validated generic template. Consumer AST infers concrete arguments from immediate evidence and emits requests.

The build system deduplicates requests. The compiler materialises concrete generated functions into sidecars and validates them before backend handoff.

HIR never carries unsolved generic calls.

## Traits

Traits and conformances are static frontend evidence. AST validates evidence and resolves bound-provided calls to concrete targets.

There are no trait objects, erased runtime dispatch or backend trait solving.

## Casts

Explicit casts use compiler-owned target policy and evidence. Foldable conversions happen in AST. Runtime conversions become explicit checked HIR operations or direct source calls.

Contextual coercion remains separate from explicit casting.

## Rewrite focus

Explain monomorphisation, evidence, static dispatch, explicit conversion and why each abstraction disappears or becomes concrete before HIR.

Canonical details live in `docs/compiler-design-overview.md`.
